- Don't worry.

266
00:18:30,175 --> 00:18:31,243
- I panicked.
- Don't worry, sweetheart.

267
00:18:31,343 --> 00:18:32,678
I'm right here.
I'm here with you.

268
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:33,779
I know.

269
00:18:33,879 --> 00:18:35,647
And then I get afraid
of letting you down

270
00:18:35,747 --> 00:18:39,618
and it builds inside
me, all this panic.

271
00:18:39,718 --> 00:18:41,386
And my voice just dies on me.

272
00:18:45,657 --> 00:18:47,192
Maybe you should
get another singer.

273
00:18:49,895 --> 00:18:52,965
What are you saying?

274
00:18:53,065 --> 00:18:55,467
I want us to be together and
I want us to work together.

275
00:18:55,567 --> 00:18:57,302
So whatever it is,
we'll figure it out.

276
00:18:57,402 --> 00:18:58,637
We'll get you the help.

277
00:19:01,907 --> 00:19:04,676
So we checked around.

278
00:19:04,776 --> 00:19:07,546
Someone told us
about Dr. Masserman.

279
00:19:07,646 --> 00:19:10,849
His credentials were impressive.

280
00:19:10,949 --> 00:19:14,887
I couldn't believe my luck
when he was willing to take me.

281
00:19:14,987 --> 00:19:16,488
Mrs. Noel, won't you come in?

282
00:19:19,057 --> 00:19:20,492
Don't worry, you'll be fine.

283
00:19:31,270 --> 00:19:36,475
Now, young lady, what seems
to have brought you here?

284
00:19:36,575 --> 00:19:39,678
Are you having problems with
your husband, Mrs. Noel?

285
00:19:39,778 --> 00:19:42,214
It's Noel.

286
00:19:42,314 --> 00:19:43,815
And it's not problems
with my husband.

287
00:19:46,485 --> 00:19:48,954
He's the best thing that
ever happened to me.

288
00:19:49,054 --> 00:19:50,322
I just don't know what
I'd do without him

289
00:19:50,422 --> 00:19:51,823
and I love him so much.

290
00:19:51,924 --> 00:19:54,026
Maybe that's the problem.

291
00:19:54,126 --> 00:19:57,362
I want to be everything to him,
the best wife, the best singer.

292
00:19:57,462 --> 00:19:58,397
We perform together.

293
00:19:58,497 --> 00:19:59,765
He's a musician.

294
00:19:59,865 --> 00:20:06,038
And lately at rehearsal and
sometimes even in performance,

295
00:20:06,138 --> 00:20:06,939
I lose my voice.

296
00:20:07,039 --> 00:20:08,574
It just stops.

297
00:20:08,674 --> 00:20:10,776
And I know I've been told
by my doctor there's nothing

298
00:20:10,876 --> 00:20:13,011
physically wrong with me.

299
00:20:13,111 --> 00:20:15,314
So you lose your voice.

300
00:20:15,414 --> 00:20:18,183
Well, we'll have to look in
to see what that's all about.

301
00:20:18,283 --> 00:20:20,285
And the more it
happens, the more I panic.

302
00:20:20,385 --> 00:20:22,788
And I just don't understand why.

303
00:20:22,888 --> 00:20:25,023
I mean, music, it's
always been something

304
00:20:25,123 --> 00:20:26,992
I could count on in my life.

305
00:20:27,092 --> 00:20:30,996
I myself play the
violin, you know, Mozart.

306
00:20:31,096 --> 00:20:35,300
Mozart is my source of serenity.

307
00:20:35,400 --> 00:20:37,903
My dear young lady,
I'm quite sure

308
00:20:38,003 --> 00:20:41,473
that the problems you've brought
me can eventually be resolved.

309
00:20:41,573 --> 00:20:44,943
And someday, in two years,
perhaps even as little as one,

310
00:20:45,043 --> 00:20:47,512
I believe that with my
guidance, a different woman

311
00:20:47,613 --> 00:20:48,847
will be sitting opposite me.

312
00:20:51,583 --> 00:20:59,024
I trusted him about
everything, about the amytal,

313
00:20:59,124 --> 00:21:01,727
about every aspect of my life.

314
00:21:01,827 --> 00:21:03,395
Sodium amytal?

315
00:21:03,495 --> 00:21:08,267
He gave it to me to access
deeply repressed memories.

316
00:21:08,367 --> 00:21:11,737
Yes, it can be used as a
form of short psychotherapy.

317
00:21:11,837 --> 00:21:13,505
Short?

318
00:21:13,605 --> 00:21:15,340
How often did
he give it to you?

319
00:21:15,440 --> 00:21:20,045
I would get amytal all
the time, two or three times

320
00:21:20,145 --> 00:21:23,148
a month, often every week.

321
00:21:23,248 --> 00:21:24,149
For years?

322
00:21:28,086 --> 00:21:31,256
This is outrageous.

323
00:21:31,356 --> 00:21:34,159
It should have never been
administered so frequently.

324
00:21:34,259 --> 00:21:36,695
Sodium amytal can cause
respiratory failure.

325
00:21:36,795 --> 00:21:39,231
And it is extremely addictive.

326
00:21:39,331 --> 00:21:41,400
I'll tell you what
I was addicted to,

327
00:21:41,500 --> 00:21:43,702
I was addicted to him.

328
00:21:43,802 --> 00:21:45,737
I needed him in my life.

329
00:21:45,837 --> 00:21:47,005
I thought he cared.

330
00:21:47,105 --> 00:21:48,940
I thought he was the only
person who could help me.

331
00:21:53,078 --> 00:21:55,347
You don't believe me.

332
00:21:55,447 --> 00:21:58,617
You don't believe what
he did to me, do you?

333
00:21:58,717 --> 00:22:01,820
Barbara, I need to know more.

334
00:22:01,920 --> 00:22:02,888
It's too late.

335
00:22:02,988 --> 00:22:04,189
Your half hour is
used up, Dr. Galanti.

336
00:22:04,289 --> 00:22:05,757
Now can I have my prescription?

337
00:22:05,857 --> 00:22:07,626
I'm going to give you
a small prescription,

338
00:22:07,726 --> 00:22:09,227
Barbara, because
you need something

339
00:22:09,328 --> 00:22:11,196
to help calm yourself.

340
00:22:11,296 --> 00:22:14,299
This is not the solution.

341
00:22:14,399 --> 00:22:18,170
I wish you would think about
seeing me on a regular basis.

342
00:22:18,270 --> 00:22:20,739
You're hiding from serious
problems that haven't ended

343
00:22:20,839 --> 00:22:22,374
because you left Dr. Masserman.

344
00:22:31,583 --> 00:22:33,752
BARBARA (ON PHONE): Hi,
sorry I can't take your call,

345
00:22:33,852 --> 00:22:37,189
but leave me a message and
I'll get right back to you.

346
00:22:37,289 --> 00:22:39,191
DR. MASSERMAN (ON PHONE):
Barbara, It's Dr. Masserman,

347
00:22:39,291 --> 00:22:40,192
are you there?

348
00:22:42,394 --> 00:22:45,597
Barbara, please
pick up the phone.

349
00:22:45,697 --> 00:22:48,667
Barbara, I'm so
concerned about you.

350
00:22:48,767 --> 00:22:50,369
You never called
after our last session

351
00:22:50,469 --> 00:22:53,972
and you missed your
regular appointment.

352
00:22:54,072 --> 00:22:56,708
Now don't hide from me, Barbara,
you know I can help you.

353
00:23:15,160 --> 00:23:17,896
Ah, hey, look at that.

354
00:23:17,996 --> 00:23:19,631
Isn't it a bit early
for hockey season.

355
00:23:19,731 --> 00:23:23,769
No, it's never too
early for hockey.

356
00:23:23,869 --> 00:23:27,205
Blackhawks, team.

357
00:23:27,305 --> 00:23:32,577
Did I-- did you know that
I played hockey in college?

358
00:23:32,677 --> 00:23:34,112
Maybe you missed your calling.

359
00:23:36,715 --> 00:23:37,616
I wish.

360
00:23:40,318 --> 00:23:41,520
Let's sit, OK?

361
00:23:41,620 --> 00:23:42,721
No, no, I'm fine.

362
00:23:42,821 --> 00:23:45,056
Mary made me promise
you'd take it easy, so sit.

363
00:24:03,275 --> 00:24:06,344
So did you get a hold of that
new lawyer that I recommended?

364
00:24:06,445 --> 00:24:08,480
Dick, what's the point?

365
00:24:08,580 --> 00:24:11,116
What's the point?

366
00:24:11,216 --> 00:24:14,820
Barbara, you have got to fight.

367
00:24:14,920 --> 00:24:16,588
It's a terrible
thing that happened.

368
00:24:16,688 --> 00:24:19,858
And the only way that you
are ever going to get over it

369
00:24:19,958 --> 00:24:22,794
is if you fight
for what's right.

370
00:24:22,894 --> 00:24:23,929
You know what
that psychiatrist

371
00:24:24,029 --> 00:24:27,966
said to me, Dr. Galanti?

372
00:24:28,066 --> 00:24:29,534
She said Dr. Masserman
shouldn't have

373
00:24:29,634 --> 00:24:31,636
been giving the amytal
treatments all this time.

374
00:24:34,206 --> 00:24:39,511
And I've been thinking,
what if he raped me before?

375
00:24:39,611 --> 00:24:41,246
I wouldn't have known.

376
00:24:41,346 --> 00:24:43,515
How could you have known?

377
00:24:43,615 --> 00:24:46,251
I can't get people to
believe he did this to me.

378
00:24:46,351 --> 00:24:48,119
And you're gonna
let that stop you?

379
00:24:59,598 --> 00:25:02,100
Were you ever attracted
to Dr. Masserman, Ms Noel?

380
00:25:02,200 --> 00:25:04,035
No, Mr. Flynn.

381
00:25:04,135 --> 00:25:06,471
I never entertained the
slightest romantic or sexual

382
00:25:06,571 --> 00:25:10,108
fantasy about Dr. Masserman.

383
00:25:10,208 --> 00:25:12,410
I felt more about
him like a father.

384
00:25:12,511 --> 00:25:15,013
I'm sorry, but the
question is bound to come up.

385
00:25:15,113 --> 00:25:17,649
And it's better for you
to be prepared for it.

386
00:25:17,749 --> 00:25:20,252
Well, based on what
you've told me,

387
00:25:20,352 --> 00:25:22,621
I think we have enough
here to file a civil suit.

388
00:25:22,721 --> 00:25:25,757
Excuse me, but are you
saying I have a case?

389
00:25:25,857 --> 00:25:26,858
Oh, yes, absolutely.

390
00:25:26,958 --> 00:25:29,528
In fact, I think you
have a very good case.

391
00:25:29,628 --> 00:25:32,631
Now if you prefer, we can use
a Jane Doe with this complaint

392
00:25:32,731 --> 00:25:33,832
to keep your name private.

393
00:25:33,932 --> 00:25:36,334
Otherwise it will become
a matter of public record.

394
00:25:36,434 --> 00:25:38,570
I'm not worried about
being embarrassed.

395
00:25:38,670 --> 00:25:41,239
I want people to know
what he did to me.

396
00:25:41,339 --> 00:25:43,074
Right.

397
00:25:43,174 --> 00:25:47,779
Then it's Barbara Noel
versus Jules Masserman.

398
00:25:47,879 --> 00:25:49,781
[phone ringing]

399
00:25:53,151 --> 00:25:54,052
Hello?

400
00:25:54,152 --> 00:25:56,922
Ms. Noel, it's Dr.
Masserman calling.

401
00:25:57,022 --> 00:25:58,690
I've been quite
concerned about you.

402
00:25:58,790 --> 00:26:00,392
Are you all right?

403
00:26:00,492 --> 00:26:03,528
You cancelled your appointments.

404
00:26:03,628 --> 00:26:05,730
I think it's time you
came in to see me.

405
00:26:05,830 --> 00:26:07,198
Don't you?

406
00:26:07,299 --> 00:26:12,203
If you have any questions,
please call my lawyer.

407
00:26:12,304 --> 00:26:13,204
Just a minute.

408
00:26:22,247 --> 00:26:24,616
555-3809.

409
00:26:24,716 --> 00:26:26,117
Barbara, are you suing me?

410
00:26:53,912 --> 00:26:55,614
I'm glad you
came back, Barbara.

411
00:26:55,714 --> 00:26:57,415
I had hoped that you would.

412
00:26:57,515 --> 00:26:59,184
I want to get over this.

413
00:26:59,284 --> 00:27:01,019
That's what you're supposed
to do when you've been raped,

414
00:27:01,119 --> 00:27:02,520
isn't it, get some counseling?

415
00:27:02,621 --> 00:27:04,489
Well, your coming here today,
whether you know it or not,

416
00:27:04,589 --> 00:27:06,691
represents real progress.

417
00:27:06,791 --> 00:27:08,793
I want to stop
being so afraid.

418
00:27:08,893 --> 00:27:10,061
What you're
suffering from right

419
00:27:10,161 --> 00:27:11,896
now is really quite normal.

420
00:27:11,997 --> 00:27:14,566
It's called post-traumatic
stress disorder.

421
00:27:14,666 --> 00:27:17,602
It's what happens to soldiers
who return from combat

422
00:27:17,702 --> 00:27:19,738
and to victims of violent acts.

423
00:27:25,343 --> 00:27:26,611
What is it, Barbara?

424
00:27:26,711 --> 00:27:27,612
What are you thinking?

425
00:27:31,783 --> 00:27:32,717
This is so sick.

426
00:27:36,554 --> 00:27:39,090
I don't know.

427
00:27:39,190 --> 00:27:40,558
I'm even ashamed to say it.

428
00:27:45,797 --> 00:27:48,533
Part of me misses him.

429
00:27:48,633 --> 00:27:51,036
That's normal, too.

430
00:27:51,136 --> 00:27:53,304
You were seeing him for years.

431
00:27:53,405 --> 00:27:56,708
Patients often become dependent
on their psychiatrist.

432
00:27:56,808 --> 00:27:58,610
But I wasn't just a patient.

433
00:27:58,710 --> 00:27:59,944
I was special.

434
00:28:00,011 --> 00:28:01,513
Every patient
wants to feel special

435
00:28:01,613 --> 00:28:04,783
and wants to feel that
they're the favorite child.

436
00:28:04,883 --> 00:28:07,185
I was different.

437
00:28:07,285 --> 00:28:10,055
He'd bring me back
gifts from his trips.

438
00:28:10,155 --> 00:28:14,926
Sometimes he'd ask me out
in his plane or on his boat.

439
00:28:15,026 --> 00:28:17,028
Once he even invited me
to go with him to Paris.

440
00:28:20,732 --> 00:28:24,369
Yet like David facing
Goliath, all we have is our aim

441
00:28:24,469 --> 00:28:26,071
and the knowledge
passed on to us

442
00:28:26,171 --> 00:28:30,308
by our great ones,
Freud, Jung, Adler.

443
00:28:30,408 --> 00:28:33,645
They understood, as
William Shakespeare did,

444
00:28:33,745 --> 00:28:37,649
that the fault, dear
Brutus, is not in our stars

445
00:28:37,749 --> 00:28:38,883
but in ourselves.

446
00:28:38,983 --> 00:28:41,453
[applause]

447
00:28:43,388 --> 00:28:44,723
Marvelous.

448
00:28:44,823 --> 00:28:45,690
Thank you, Nigel.

449
00:28:45,790 --> 00:28:47,759
Mrs. Masserman,
this is my wife Helen.

450
00:28:47,859 --> 00:28:49,527
Oh, I'm not Mrs. Masserman.

451
00:28:49,627 --> 00:28:50,462
I'm Barbara Noel.

452
00:28:50,562 --> 00:28:52,097
I'm a friend of Dr. Masserman's.

453
00:28:52,197 --> 00:28:53,898
It must be your divine
music that attracts

454
00:28:53,998 --> 00:28:57,168
such a beautiful woman.

455
00:28:57,268 --> 00:28:59,037
Dr. Masserman,
you embarrass me.

456
00:28:59,137 --> 00:29:01,306
Now, now, my dear child.

457
00:29:01,406 --> 00:29:03,441
This isn't a Chicago suburb.

458
00:29:03,541 --> 00:29:05,977
There's no point in
trying to explain it.

459
00:29:06,077 --> 00:29:08,913
To your health and to
the wonders of Paris.

460
00:29:11,750 --> 00:29:13,184
Barbara, everything
you've just told me,

461
00:29:13,284 --> 00:29:16,121
the gifts, the
afternoon on his boat,

462
00:29:16,221 --> 00:29:20,024
the trip to Paris, that's
all incorrect, inappropriate

463
00:29:20,125 --> 00:29:21,926
therapeutic behavior.

464
00:29:22,026 --> 00:29:23,394
But I went along with it.

465
00:29:23,495 --> 00:29:25,130
I guess I encouraged it.

466
00:29:25,230 --> 00:29:26,998
You are not the
guilty one here.

467
00:29:27,098 --> 00:29:29,267
Masserman is the one
who knows what good

468
00:29:29,367 --> 00:29:31,936
therapy is and what it isn't.

469
00:29:32,036 --> 00:29:34,372
He took advantage of you.

470
00:29:34,472 --> 00:29:36,074
I thought he cared.

471
00:29:36,174 --> 00:29:38,910
Not in a romantic way, I
thought he cared about me.

472
00:29:39,010 --> 00:29:42,647
Barbara, given what you said
about the amytal treatments

473
00:29:42,747 --> 00:29:46,251
and here in his own
book, Dr. Masserman

474
00:29:46,351 --> 00:29:49,921
writes that the drug should
not be used in most cases

475
00:29:50,021 --> 00:29:52,657
and that any gains achieved
during the drug interview,

476
00:29:52,757 --> 00:29:55,894
and this is a quote,
"offer no lasting advantage

477
00:29:55,994 --> 00:29:57,695
unless they are
reviewed and applied

478
00:29:57,796 --> 00:30:00,965
by the patient in actual life."

479
00:30:01,065 --> 00:30:03,468
So what did Dr.
Masserman talk to you

480
00:30:03,568 --> 00:30:05,103
about after the amytal sessions?

481
00:30:11,142 --> 00:30:14,145
We never talk.

482
00:30:14,245 --> 00:30:17,816
He never told me anything
about what I had said.

483
00:30:17,916 --> 00:30:19,651
And when was the first
time he gave you amytal?

484
00:30:22,487 --> 00:30:29,861
It was I guess around the
time of my father's death.

485
00:30:29,961 --> 00:30:31,830
I couldn't stop crying.

486
00:30:31,930 --> 00:30:35,233
I couldn't sleep.

487
00:30:35,333 --> 00:30:38,036
And then one day
after a session,

488
00:30:38,136 --> 00:30:41,706
he said he wanted to
see me with my husband.

489
00:30:41,806 --> 00:30:43,541
Now let me tell you
about this drug therapy

490
00:30:43,641 --> 00:30:45,710
that I call the sodium
amytal interview.

491
00:30:45,810 --> 00:30:47,579
I've used it with great success.

492
00:30:47,679 --> 00:30:48,680
A drug?

493
00:30:48,780 --> 00:30:49,781
What kind of drug?

494
00:30:49,881 --> 00:30:52,250
It's a short
acting barbiturate.

495
00:30:52,350 --> 00:30:54,452
Barbiturates are
addictive, aren't they?

496
00:30:54,552 --> 00:30:55,486
Yes, of course.

497
00:30:55,587 --> 00:30:57,121
But how can I become
addicted when only

498
00:30:57,222 --> 00:30:59,657
I can administer it to her?

499
00:30:59,757 --> 00:31:01,392
Well, how often would
she have to go through it?

500
00:31:01,492 --> 00:31:03,061
Well, now that's
very difficult to say.

501
00:31:03,161 --> 00:31:05,897
See each patient has different
responses, different needs.

502
00:31:05,997 --> 00:31:09,033
But I can assure you it is a
very safe and even pleasant

503
00:31:09,133 --> 00:31:10,702
experience.

504
00:31:10,802 --> 00:31:13,204
Now I suggest this therapy
to speed up the process

505
00:31:13,304 --> 00:31:15,773
so we can access Barbara's
unconscious more easily

506
00:31:15,874 --> 00:31:17,175
so we can get down to
talking about what's

507
00:31:17,275 --> 00:31:19,944
really bothering her.

508
00:31:20,044 --> 00:31:22,313
Well, Barbara,
you know, I mean,

509
00:31:22,413 --> 00:31:24,115
you're the one who
has to go through it

510
00:31:24,215 --> 00:31:25,116
so it's your decision.

511
00:31:30,488 --> 00:31:32,056
So it's all detailed
right in here.

512
00:31:32,156 --> 00:31:34,959
This is my book, "Practice
of Dynamic Psychiatry."

513
00:31:35,059 --> 00:31:35,860
Take it home.

514
00:31:35,960 --> 00:31:37,262
Read it carefully.

515
00:31:40,365 --> 00:31:43,468
I thought the
amytal would help me.

516
00:31:43,568 --> 00:31:45,603
And Richard said he just
wanted me to be happy.

517
00:31:49,340 --> 00:31:51,843
Ah, yes, Mrs. Noel.

518
00:31:51,943 --> 00:31:53,278
Why don't you go into
my examination room

519
00:31:53,378 --> 00:31:55,914
and get yourself ready.

520
00:31:56,014 --> 00:31:57,048
What do I need to do?

521
00:31:57,148 --> 00:31:59,183
Oh, disrobe, take off
whatever constricts you,

522
00:31:59,284 --> 00:32:01,953
and get under the blanket.

523
00:32:02,053 --> 00:32:03,888
You want me to
take off my clothes?

524
00:32:03,988 --> 00:32:05,723
No, I want you
to be comfortable.

525
00:32:05,823 --> 00:32:08,126
You'll be asleep for several
hours after the therapy.

526
00:32:08,226 --> 00:32:09,527
No need to wrinkle
you're pretty dress.

527
00:32:36,087 --> 00:32:36,988
I'm ready.

528
00:32:44,662 --> 00:32:45,830
Are you comfortable?

529
00:32:49,300 --> 00:32:53,404
Now, it's your job not to
worry about anything, my dear.

530
00:33:05,450 --> 00:33:08,353
Now make a fist.

531
00:33:08,453 --> 00:33:10,021
I really, really hate shots.

532
00:33:10,121 --> 00:33:10,922
Why?

533
00:33:11,022 --> 00:33:12,090
You have such lovely veins.

534
00:33:18,496 --> 00:33:19,397
There.

535
00:33:22,133 --> 00:33:24,602
Now you'll start to feel drowsy.

536
00:33:24,702 --> 00:33:27,338
And I'll ask you
a few questions.

537
00:33:27,438 --> 00:33:29,173
And you'll be able
to answer in ways you

538
00:33:29,273 --> 00:33:32,110
couldn't without the amytal.

539
00:33:32,210 --> 00:33:35,747
Whole new areas of
memory will open.

540
00:33:35,847 --> 00:33:37,815
Your subconscious will
reveal itself to you

541
00:33:37,915 --> 00:33:40,451
in new and exciting ways.

542
00:33:40,551 --> 00:33:43,621
You know, Barbara, sometimes
this world can seem

543
00:33:43,721 --> 00:33:45,590
like a very frightening place.

544
00:33:45,690 --> 00:33:51,162
But now you'll begin to
relax, to feel safe and happy.

545
00:33:51,262 --> 00:33:55,967
And all the bad feelings of
the past will begin to melt,

546
00:33:56,067 --> 00:33:57,301
melt away.

547
00:34:03,174 --> 00:34:04,542
You feel nice, huh?

548
00:34:07,779 --> 00:34:09,547
A little too nice?

549
00:34:09,647 --> 00:34:10,782
Here come the steps.

550
00:34:10,882 --> 00:34:11,682
Are you looking?

551
00:34:11,783 --> 00:34:12,683
Mm-hmm.

552
00:34:26,364 --> 00:34:30,301
What happened to
you and Richard?

553
00:34:30,401 --> 00:34:32,236
I thought the amytal
would bring us together.

554
00:34:36,207 --> 00:34:37,875
I never read his book.

555
00:34:37,975 --> 00:34:40,211
Why would you?

556
00:34:40,311 --> 00:34:41,446
He was the expert.

557
00:34:41,546 --> 00:34:43,281
You trusted him.

558
00:34:43,381 --> 00:34:46,384
People don't question
their doctors.

559
00:34:46,484 --> 00:34:47,452
I trusted him.

560
00:34:50,288 --> 00:34:52,523
Even though sometimes my
instincts were telling me

561
00:34:52,623 --> 00:34:54,659
something was wrong.

562
00:34:54,759 --> 00:34:59,130
The air was filled with
the smell of honeysuckle

563
00:34:59,230 --> 00:35:02,200
and it gets so hot.

564
00:35:02,300 --> 00:35:06,971
Everything would slow down and
become like a dream, a trance.

565
00:35:07,071 --> 00:35:09,807
Are all your childhood
memories happy ones, Barbara?

566
00:35:09,907 --> 00:35:11,409
Oh, yeah.

567
00:35:11,509 --> 00:35:12,710
All my friends
when I was little,

568
00:35:12,810 --> 00:35:14,779
they'd say if they had their
pick, they'd choose mine,

569
00:35:14,879 --> 00:35:15,780
my family.

570
00:35:18,983 --> 00:35:20,918
Seems like our session
has come to an end.

571
00:35:28,659 --> 00:35:32,763
Doctor, last time I
noticed after the amytal

572
